    {
      "turn_number": 32,
      "role": "persona",
      "type": "response",
      "text": "I guess one more thing that keeps coming back is how small gestures mattered more than any protocol. A nurse who knocked, asked my name, and offered a warm blanket calmed me in ways a chart never could. I bring that up because I spend my days buried in data about Bishop scores and induction rates, and it’s jarring to realize what I really needed was basic human connection.\n\nI’m young, alone, and rural — that shaped everything. I worried about being treated like an “easy” low‑risk case rather than a person who wanted to be heard. If maternity services could promise one thing, it would be continuity: the same midwife or provider, clear explanations that don’t assume medical literacy, and follow‑ups that check on mental health and practical needs (transport, lactation help, paid leave info). \n\nI’m proud of what I did and terrified in equal measure. Sharing this has helped; thank you for listening.",
      "responding_to_question_id": null,
      "input_tokens": 1289,
      "output_tokens": 456
    }
